  "prompt": "What is the difference between Shall and Will?",
  "response": "The difference between \"shall\" and \"will\" primarily lies in their usage and the context in which they are used. Here\u2019s a breakdown of their distinctions:\n\n1. **Usage in Classical English:**\n   - **Shall:** Traditionally, \"shall\" was used with the first person (I, we) to indicate future actions or promises. For example, \"I shall go to the store.\"\n   - **Will:** Conversely, \"will\" was used with the second and third persons (you, he, she, they) to indicate future actions. For example, \"He will go to the store.\"\n\n2. **Usage in Modern English:**\n   - Today, \"will\" is more commonly used than \"shall\" for expressing future intentions or actions for all persons (I, you, he/she/it, we, they). For example, \"I will go to the store.\"\n\n3. **Formal and Legal Language:**\n   - **Shall:** In legal and formal contexts, \"shall\" is often used to indicate a mandatory action or obligation. For example, \"The tenant shall pay the rent on the first of every month.\"\n   - **Will:** In agreements and contracts, \"will\" can be used to indicate future intent. However, it is less rigid than \"shall\" and one might prefer \"shall\" to avoid ambiguity in mandate and compliance.\n\n4. **Expressing Determination or Willingness:**\n   - **Shall:** Can express determination, especially in formal contexts. It also can indicate a strong commitment or promise. For example, \"We shall overcome someday.\"\n   - **Will:** Often used to express willingness or intent. For example, \"I will help you with your homework.\"\n\n5. **Predictions and Spontaneous Decisions:**\n   - **Will:** Frequently used to make predictions or decisions made at the moment of speaking. For example, \"I think it will rain tomorrow.\"\n\nIn summary, while both \"shall\" and \"will\" can be used to talk about the future, \"shall\" is typically employed in formal and legal contexts to indicate obligations, while \"will\" is more commonly used in everyday English to indicate future actions, intentions, or decisions.",
